[18:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'another which if you think about it, is actually quite useful and convenient. For example, if it\'s picking up an object and needs to place it somewhere behind itself, it doesn\'t have to like completely turn its body with its feet'

[18:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to face the other direction like a human. This robot can just rotate its torso or its arms to place the item behind it. You know, for all the other humanoid robots like the Unitree or Optimus, they\'re basically designed to'

[18:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'look and function like a human. It walks on two legs, it\'s forward facing and it has two arms with hands. But if you think about it, there\'s no real reason for robot design to be limited to just the human form. Instead of being forward'

[18:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'facing, why not design a robot that can have its torso and all its limbs rotate in any direction it wants. So this design from the Boston Dynamics Atlas shows how a robot can be designed beyond'

[19:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just humanoid constraints to become even more efficient or powerful. All right, next up this AI is pretty interesting. It\'s called Morph Any 3D and this can basically create smooth morphs or'

[19:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transitions between two different 3D objects even if they belong to very different categories. So here\'s a simple one for example, for the input we can have Ivysaur and for the results, we can'

[19:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have Venusaur and this AI would basically generate the transitions or the morphs between the input and the output as you can see here. Or here\'s another example where we can plug in one'

[19:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Pokémon and have it transition into a completely different Pokémon like this. It would still work. Here\'s another example where we have two completely unrelated Pokémon generate a smooth'

[19:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transition from one Pokémon to the other. Now, instead of Pokémon, here are some other examples with other characters, and again, the transition is quite seamless. Even if the two'

[20:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'characters are completely unrelated, it can still generate these smooth transformations. Or, here\'s another example where we can transform this station into this castle, or even this horse into a ship. Now, normally, this'

[20:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is actually very hard to do because objects can be very different in shape or structure. It\'s really hard to keep the morph semantically consistent, so it looks natural. And it\'s hard to make the'

[20:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sequence smooth over time. But, Morph Any 3D is able to solve this without training a separate model. Now, we have had some other similar tools in the past, but as you can see here, Morph Any'

[20:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '3D, which is on the bottom right, is by far the most consistent and accurate in generating these 3D transitions. Now, here\'s how it works. Here\'s the architecture, and it consists of a few'

[20:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'key components like this morphing cross-attention, which basically mixes features of both the source and the target shapes in the attention layers of the 3D generator to maintain a coherent'

[21:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'structure. And then, it also has this temporal fusion self-attention block, which uses information from the previous frames to make the transition smoother over time. And then, finally, it has'

[21:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this orientation correction, which basically aligns the pose and orientation of both objects so that they remain consistent across the transition. Now, if you scroll up to the top of the page, they have released a GitHub repo,'

[21:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and here it says the code will be released after the paper is accepted. So, stay tuned for that. Anyways, if you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Next up, this AI is'

